<taxonomicName box="[514,792,1829,1852]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Marinussaurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="23" pageNumber="174" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="curupira">
<emphasis box="[514,792,1829,1852]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Marinussaurus curupira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to Brazilian 
<taxonomicName box="[1082,1200,1828,1853]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="23" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, and until now only known from the municipally of Iranduba, state of 
<collectingRegion box="[723,844,1864,1888]" country="Brazil" name="Amazonas" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
, just west of the confluence of Solimões and Negro Rivers (
<figureCitation box="[241,326,1900,1925]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1552,1574]" captionTargetBox="[157,1428,633,1523]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,625,1531]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 12. Distribution of examined material of Loxopholis ferreirai and Marinussaurus curupira." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581987/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="174">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
). It is terrestrial and diurnal, inhabits the leaf litter of terra firme forest (personal communication with V. Carvalho).
</paragraph>
